data.name: HomeCookieInformationText
data.value:
According to the Electronic Communications Act (2003) all visitors to a website need to be informed if cookies are used and how they can be blocked.

A cookie is a little file which is added to your computer when you visit a website. Any subsequent visits to the website are tracked by the cookie. Analysis portal web application uses cookies to generate visitor statistics which are used to improve the website. They are also used to maintain preferences for website design, functionality and language. This data is anonymous.

If you do not want cookies enabled on your computer you can block them in your web browser's security settings. You will find more information in your web browser's help function. But note that disabling cookies may do your pages to work improperly .

All data collected is anonymous.

data.name: SharedAnalysisPortalSummary
data.value: The objective of Swedish LifeWatch is to make all major national biodiversity databases in Sweden interoperable, and thereby accessible through standardized web services. The Analysis portal provides a single access point to all data connected to the infrastructure, together with a range of analytical services.

data.name: TextCitation
data.value:
For research publications and all other kinds of reports that have used the Analysis Portal, please add the following credits:

“Data used in this study were downloaded from the Swedish LifeWatch Analysis Portal [date of download and chosen data providers]. The Analysis Portal is funded by the Swedish Research Council and the Swedish Environmental Protection Agency through the Swedish LifeWatch Project (Grant No. 829-2009-6287).”

We strongly recommended that you also declare the Data Providers the analysis were run with. Such a list you can find in the species observation provenance report on the Analysis Portal (https://www.analysisportal.se/Result/ProvenanceReport).

data.name: IntroductionText
data.value:
How to get started

  1. Select data source
    > Data > Species observation
  2. Add filter and choose taxa
    > Filter > Taxa > Search by taxon name
  3. Change settings for data calculations
    > Calculation > Grid statistics > Select grid parameters e.g. size
  4. Optionally change settings for the format and maps
  5. View results
    > Result > e.g. Species observation map
  6. Change your selection or analysis, it is always possible to go directly to the result button!

Your current settings are always shown on the right side => My settings

data.name: FilterTemporalHelpInstructions
data.value:
Date & Date annually - What is the difference?

Date

With this setting you set the exact dates between which the observations you want to get is observed/registered/changed.

Date annually

With this setting you set annually between what month and day observations you want to get is observed/registered/changed.
For example. If you specify From: 2013-02-01 To: 2013-03-31, then you get observations with observed/registered/changed date between February 1 to March 31 for all years until today.
